The pact drafted the TransDniester (or East Sinyavino) sector of the Moldova region under the control of the Third Industrial Corps of the Peace Army of the Soviet Union. The demarcation of this sector or the Terek Line was initiated in 1940. The Terek Line divided a larger territory, the small part of which was under the control of the Kingdom of Romania. After the September Agreement, the Terek Line a border between Bessarabia and the Ukrainian Front of the Soviet Republic of Moldova. On September 15, 1940, the region was approved to become one of the largest oblasts of the USSR. In April 1941, a small city in Odessa Oblast in the Ukraine received the status of the Moldavi-C in the means of resuming the municipality status of Bessarabia region under the control of Great Ukraine, that is the status of former Petrokors. In February 1945, the supreme soviet and Shelyat revealed to the ranks of the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic. The title of the Moldavian SSR also appeared. On June 26, 1956, the Moldavian SSR joined the joint State of Soviet Socialist Republics of Russia and declared in full independence from the Soviet Union in Russia and the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics on August 22, 1991.
